<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
The NDA has been lifted!<P>Yeah I know about the email account. I haven't had a stable one in quite along time. Which explains why i'm not on the arsec list.<P>I was on ICQ last night, but you weren't there. I spoke with Susano and Irbs though.<P>Anyhow, I don't play on Midguard any longer, but when I did, FoH was playing. I'm glad I don't have to deal with the likes of them, since I play in Albion now(Where the actual city of Camelot is). I logged on (to Midguard) a few days ago playing a Thane and nobody from our guild was on ;P I don't even know if they reformed it.<P>About the game...I love it. I haven't had the chance to play a high level character yet, but I have played 7/8 classes to 8+.<P>In Albion i've played a Briton Paladin (level 11 *Deleted*), Highlander Mercenary (level 12), Briton Friar (Level 11), Avalonian Theurgist (level 8 *Deleted*), and a Highlander Armsman (Current Main, level 12).<P>In Midguard i've had a Huntress (level 9), and a Thane (Level 6)<P>In Hibernia i've played a Eldritch (level 8).<P>As you can see I like Albion the best. Midguard is too dark/gloomy for my tastes, Hibernia is just too fruity. Albion also seems to have a richer backstory (of course), and it has had the most work put into it since it has been around the longest.<P>My favorite character is the Highlander Armsman. The Mercenary is fun, but since dual wield is broken (because of damage modifiers) it does the same or perhaps even less damage then a Armsman with a Polearm weapon (I hit for 115 on grays, which is as much as it sounds). <P>So the Mercenary at the present time, is basically a gimped Armsman. The armsman can wear plate (merc is limited to chain), has more hp, has better taunts skills then the Mercenary.<P>The paladin is a decent class, but really not what i'm looking for. The Armsman is close (in roleplaying terms) to the paladin, but has a ranged weapon (Armsman can use crossbows), has more HP, and does more damage. The paladins advantage is nice but doesn't make up (IMO) for the things they lack. With the paladins chants you have a choice of one of three at any given time.<P>They work somewhat like a bard actually, its quite strange coming from EQ. They have a healing chant (Restores a small amount of HP a tick in battle), a Shield chant (Adds to Armor Factor, same thing as AC in EQ), and a weapon damage increase Chant (Adds a small amount of damage on to every hit with your weapon). The chants works on everyone in your group as well.<P>The Friar is a fine class, very fun. The problem I had with them is that they are treated like Clerics in EQ, and essentially, they are one. People who loved playing Clerics in EQ, but wanted to do some damage, will probably pick this class. They are almost a cross between a Monk and a Cleric. <P>They have most every spell the clerics have, and they get them at the same level. But they are not as effective as Clerics, simply because they don't have as large of a mana pool. They do nasty damage as well in Melee, but are unable to take many hits. They somewhat make up for that with their high Evade skill (Its goes up to 4, which is the highiest of any class in the game). In pure melee damage, they come close to my Armsman.<P>The Theurgist is a nice class (Sow type spell, pets, ok DD, stuns, and some other utility spells) but to me they are just...boring. Maybe its just personal opinion (i've always leaned towards melee classes), but I felt as though there was something missing. They are excellent soloers in my experience. Some people claim they are lousy, perhaps they weren't playing them right or I was too low level.<P>I have deleted my Theurgist to make room since there is only 4 slots per realm in beta.<P>The Armsman, who I am playing now as my main, is a fantasic class. They are essentially the warrior of the realm...the pure fighter. They get to wear chain armor very early (I think 5?) and plate early as well (level 15, ooo I can't wait). The only other class in the game that can wear plate is the paladin. They have the highest HP's in the realm, they do serious melee damage, and are only shadowed by the Paladin in AF (Again, AF is to DAoC as AC is to EQ) and that is only when the Paladin has his Shield taunt up (If you in a group with a paladin, you also get the shield benefits). <P>The armsman may use any weapon (Save the longbow, which is reserved for the scout). They are great soloers with the right equipment (I can solo a yellow and a blue at the same time, and take some orange mobs solo. Blue = lower level, yellow = equal level, orange = higher level). Of course, I do have the best equipment possible for my character, at my current level.<P>On to Midguard. The huntress/Hunter is a good class. Weak in PvE, but I hear they excell in realm vs realm combat due to their bows. I can charm animals indefinatly (They never break charm once charmed) that are green, and insects that are green. I deal massive damage from very long distances with my bow, but hunters are limited in what they can do in melee when said mob/person gets close. They also have personal shield spells, which helps since their armor is limited (I believe leather is the higher armor you can buy, I may be wrong)<P>I only tried the Thane to level 6, so I won't comment on them. They seemed ok. I hear they are overpowered (They have strong DD spells, wear the best armor in the realm, and can melee well) but this isn't speaking from Experience.<P>And finally the Eldritch who I was orginally planning on playing, before I got into beta. Good class, they are a wizard with more spells and slightly higher damage spells (compared to the wizard of Albion). They are a bit frustrating to play because, like the wizard, they can only take a few hits. One mistake/ a resist or two in soloing means death. They are also boring (Personal opinion of course) because there isn't much to work with. You start combat with a bolt, wait till it gets in range for normal spells, fire two DD's off, and hit quickcast (A skill where your next spell uses more mana then normal, but casts faster. It has a timer so you cant chain cast with it however), fire off another spell to hopefully finish the job.<P>Caster classes are also harder to play in DAoC then EQ, because you cannot cast a spell (No chance whatsoever) while something is attacking you.<P>Well I should probably end this because I doubt you wanted to read a book about the game heh. If you have any questions feel free to ask...<P>And let me apologise in advance for any words mispelled, grammar mistakes in this post. I really don't feel like reviewing that massive post to check, and I don't have MS word installed. =)
</FONT>
